# Polymarket UI — Cursor Agent Rules

## Project Overview

Telegram Mini App (Web App) dashboard for the Polymarket ML Trading System.
Frontend-only repository; the backend API lives at https://github.com/MarchenkoRuslan/polymarket.

**All code, comments, and documentation must be in English.**

## Tech Stack

- **Vanilla JavaScript** (ES modules, no framework, no build step)
- **Chart.js 4** (loaded via CDN, pinned to 4.4.7)
- **Telegram Web App SDK** (loaded via CDN)
- **`serve`** as static file server for dev/production
- **PWA** with service worker and manifest

## Architecture

```
public/
├── index.html            — SPA entry point
├── manifest.json         — PWA manifest
├── sw.js                 — Service worker (cache-first for shell, stale-while-revalidate for CDN)
├── css/app.css           — All styles (CSS custom properties, mobile-first)
├── icons/                — SVG icons for PWA
└── js/
    ├── app.js            — Entry: nav setup, route registration, Telegram WebApp init
    ├── api.js            — Fetch-based API client with retries + AbortController
    ├── config.js         — API_BASE_URL constant
    ├── router.js         — Hash-based SPA router with scroll-to-top
    ├── theme.js          — Telegram theme / dark mode support
    ├── utils.js          — Sanitization (escapeHtml, escapeAttr, sanitizeUrl, stripHtml),
    │                       formatters, DOM helpers, loading/error states
    ├── charts.js         — Chart.js wrappers with crosshair plugin, tooltips
    └── screens/
        ├── home.js       — Dashboard: status, KPIs, signal summary, top markets, auto-refresh
        ├── markets.js    — Searchable/paginated market list with signals & volume
        ├── marketDetail.js — Price chart, orderbook strip, stats, technicals, signals, P&L
        ├── signals.js    — ML signals: doughnut, distribution, per-market bars, market names
        ├── performance.js — Cumulative P&L, profit by market, spread timeline
        └── news.js       — RSS news cards with HTML-stripped summaries
```

## Backend API

- Base URL: `https://polymarket-predictor.up.railway.app/api/v1`
- Swagger: https://polymarket-predictor.up.railway.app/docs
- Endpoints: /status, /analytics, /markets, /markets/{id}, /trades, /orderbook, /signals, /features, /news, /results

## Key Conventions

1. **No build step** — files are served as-is from `public/`. No TypeScript, no bundler.
2. **ES Modules** — all JS files use `import`/`export`. Entry loaded with `type="module"`.
3. **Hash routing** — routes are `#home`, `#markets`, `#market/{id}`, `#signals`, `#performance`, `#news`.
4. **Screen render pattern** — each screen exports `async function render(container, ...params)`.
5. **HTML escaping** — always use `escapeHtml()` / `escapeAttr()` from `utils.js` for user content. Use `sanitizeUrl()` for href attributes. Use `stripHtml()` to clean HTML from API text fields.
6. **AbortController** — call `getSignalController()` at the start of each screen render; check `err.name === 'AbortError'` in catch.
7. **Chart cleanup** — `destroyAllCharts()` is called automatically on route change via the router.
8. **Mobile-first CSS** — CSS custom properties for theming, responsive breakpoints at 480px and 768px.
9. **Telegram integration** — app detects Telegram WebApp SDK and adapts theme, back button, etc.
10. **Batch DOM updates** — use `DocumentFragment` for lists; avoid per-item `appendChild`.

## Common Patterns

### Adding a new screen
1. Create `public/js/screens/myScreen.js` with `export async function render(container) { ... }`
2. Register in `app.js`: `registerRoute('myscreen', myScreenRender)`
3. Add nav item to `NAV_ITEMS` if it should appear in bottom nav
4. Add to `sw.js` SHELL array for offline caching

### Adding a new API endpoint
1. Add method to `api` object in `api.js`
2. Pass `signal` parameter through for AbortController support

### Styling
- Use CSS custom properties from `:root` (e.g., `var(--bg-primary)`, `var(--accent)`)
- Dark mode uses `[data-theme="dark"]` attribute
- Telegram theme colors override CSS variables at runtime
- Always use semantic class names; avoid inline styles for reusable patterns
- Accessibility: use `aria-label`, `role`, `focus-visible` patterns
